FLASK PROJECT DEAD ENDS AND HOW I OVER CAME 
    - At the beginning, my main issue was that Docker itself was not properly running on my system. When I tried to 
    run:
        - [docker build -t flask-app .]
    - I got an error saying it could not connect to the Docker daemon. This happened because the Docker CLI depends 
    on the Docker Engine (daemon) running in the background, and on macOS this is managed by Docker Desktop. At that 
    moment, Docker Desktop was either not fully started or not ready, so even though the docker command existed, 
    there was no active backend to process requests. Later, when I ran docker info, it successfully showed server 
    information like “Docker Desktop,” which confirmed that the daemon was now running. That is why Docker commands s
    tarted working after that point.
    - Once Docker was running correctly, I was able to create a network using:
        - [docker network create flask-mysql-net]
    - This worked because user-defined networks require a running Docker engine. This network is important because it
     acts like a virtual switch that allows containers to communicate with each other using names instead of 
     IP addresses.
    - After that, I successfully started a MySQL container using:
        - [docker run -d \
            --name mysql-db \
            --network flask-mysql-net \
            -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=rootpass \
            -e MYSQL_DATABASE=mydb \
            mysql:8]
    - This worked because Docker automatically pulled the MySQL image from Docker Hub and created a container connected
     to my custom network. The key part here is the --network flask-mysql-net flag, which allowed the database container
      to be reachable by name (mysql-db) from other containers on the same network.
    - Next, I built my Flask image using:
        - [docker build -t flask-app .]
    - This worked successfully because Docker reused cached layers from previous attempts. I saw “CACHED” steps because
     Docker only rebuilds parts of the image that changed. Since my Dockerfile, app.py, and requirements.txt were already
      valid, it did not need to reinstall dependencies or repeat earlier steps.

    - After building the image, I ran my Flask container with:
        -[docker run -d \
        --name flask-app \
        --network flask-mysql-net \
        -p 5002:5002 \
        flask-app]
   - This successfully created and started the container. However, when I tried to run the same command again, Docker 
   gave me a conflict error saying the container name /flask-app was already in use. This happened because Docker container
    names must be unique, and even if a container is stopped, its name still exists until it is removed. 
   - The final working setup succeeded because both containers were placed on the same Docker network (flask-mysql-net).
    This allowed my Flask app to communicate with MySQL using the hostname mysql-db instead of an IP address or localhost.
     Inside Docker, this works because Docker provides built-in DNS resolution for container names within the same network.
   - In summary, my issues came from three main areas: first, Docker was not running initially, which prevented any commands 
   from working. Second, empty or incomplete setup files caused build issues early on. Third, container naming conflicts
    occurred because I tried to reuse the same container name without removing the old one. Once Docker was running, 
    my files were correct, and the containers were properly networked, everything worked as expected.